<span class="headline">Gates of Discord Tour for Kwill</span><br>
<span class="byline">3/4/04, 8:14 PST | <a href="mailto:kwill@planeteq.com">Kwill</a></span><br><br>
<span class="newsitem"><b>My Gates of Discord Tour</b><p>

The amazing depth of EQ design…that’s one of the first and most lasting impressions I got of my tour of the Gates of Discord expansion.  I am an active player, and therefore I spend much of my time the way most active players do, sitting in a zone getting experience, or raiding to kill the named mob, or talking with friends while running from one place to another.  On my tour, being transported from zone to zone by Brenlo, I wasn’t running from mobs, or hurrying to the camp spot, and I took the time to really look at the artwork, the animations, and the architecture of the cities and the zones we visited.  I was struck anew at the talents of the artists and the designers that give us such a fantastic world to play in.  A friend reminded me that throughout the game, even if you have been in a zone 100 times, you can still find something interesting to look at or notice.  It’s in the details.  Gates of Discord is no exception to this tradition. The artwork in Gates of Discord has taken a new, and in my opinion, exciting direction.  Showing a sense of style with stunning detail, the artwork both in the NPCs and zone architecture is complex and fun to look at.  Brenlo told us that the current art director has been leading his team to create zones and characters that are cutting edge and fresh, and I must agree. As always, there is an impressive use of color and design elements. They have updated the artwork to take advantage of the new game engine that is coming out, and are still doing a great job with the engine they work with now.  We can look forward to more efficient use of computer hardware with the new engine, as well, which will be a help in dealing with the huge graphic demands.  With this expansion, the designers and artists continue to try new ideas and techniques in game design. If you followed the progress of the Nedaria zone, you saw it grow before your eyes.  It was the first time the designers had ever changed a zone in real time by patching it, rather than just completing it in the studio and rolling it out totally finished.  Brenlo reminded us that players, if they were observant, saw the zone going from an empty piece of land to the thriving port home to the ship Queen of Thorns.<p>

The monsters in Gates are fantastical, beautiful, ugly, -- and extremely detailed, as well as scary.  Their eyes blink, individual fingers move, and they all fit into the story line of the zones in Gates of Discord.  The buildings and landscapes are detailed and seem to be a rendition of a place you might find existing somewhere in the universe.  The details in the temples, such as the artwork and building architecture, are realistic and add to the storyline as well as the atmosphere.  On temple walls, you can see the artwork for the worship of the Sea god.  The Hanging Gardens zone is a fantastical Babylon, or Aztec dream.<p>

The NPCs are developing too.  In Lost Dungeons of Norrath, we can manipulate objects such as chests.  Now NPCs are designed to manipulate objects in Gates and interact with players.  Check out Roppi the Gardener in Nedaria, or the disgruntled NPC guy who kicks around a box – fun stuff! The NPCs come alive in the world, making it more realistic and dynamic.<p>

The storyline continues to have importance in this new expansion, and the world stays seamless from one expansion to the next.  Gates of Discord is all about the rift in the lost continent, with slave races and conquering tribes.  The zones work with the story.  We visited the sewers, where we could see an elaborate water wheel turning, providing power to the city above.  I asked about the state of role playing – a lost idea it seems in the rush to get the best equipment and conquer all encounters.  The SOE team hasn’t forgotten:  the storyline is designed to allow each player to have some impact on the world.  Each player has the opportunity to be immersed in Norrath, where things are happening and the storyline is dynamic, according to Brenlo.  Players can live out the storyline, as it does have a logic and history that can be applied to the game.  So if you want to roleplay, you can: there is a logical and fairly complex storyline of the world's history to work with.<p>

Gates of Discord, like Planes of Power, uses the storyline to move players through the adventures.  Expedition zones, another type of instanced zone, are created at the request of players through asking certain NPCs for quests and tasks, creating a subgame that works with the larger expansion to advance your character in the storyline.  By completing an expedition zone, you advance and move along to new areas and deeper into the story line.  Expedition zones can have up to six players and as few as two, and are created when requested, as are the LDoN zones.   We visited an under-cavern expedition zone as an example of one of these instanced play areas.<p>

But it’s not all just scenery and atmosphere.  Gates of Discord is different from the other expansions in the type of play style required.  I have been following the discussions on various message boards about Gates, and was worried myself about playing in the zone, because although I am over 60, I am not one of those who has the best equipment or hundreds of AAs.  I asked Brenlo about the average over 50 player’s experience in Gates, and he assured me that it is accessible for players like me.  The design team didn’t make the same game in Gates however; they are asking people to think of new strategies and tactics to play in these zones.  This is not a repeat of Planes of Power, and Brenlo explained that you can’t play like you have been playing in PoP or other old world zones.  These zones require new strategies and new ways of thinking.  They are designed to be playable, for groups of 6 or guild raids – but they are not designed for zerg tactics, according to Brenlo.  When I asked about the levels of the mobs we were seeing, most of them were in the high 50s.  Good for SOE.  As EQ matures, it’s refreshing to see that an expansion is not the same old thing we all have been doing for the past five years.  New strategies and new ways of thinking about how to approach a zone and particular mobs are the order of the day.  That’s good game design.  And no, he didn’t tell me exactly how the new strategies of play were supposed to work – that’s for the players to figure out (wish he had).<p>

Some of the new features of the expansion are also worth noting.  Leadership experience, which can be toggled on by pressing the “L” key on your keyboard when you have the Gates expansion, takes 20% of your raw experience toward new skills that are useful for a group.  The new targeting system, which allows the group leader to target up to three NPCs, each with differently shaped targeting circles (even if you can’t read the number, you can learn what shape means one two or three), shows the health of the targeted NPC -- clearly indicating what mob should be mezzed, fought, or left alone according to the group or raid leader.  For those who are not targeting the mob under attack, you can still see the health of the targeted mob as a percentage number above the mob’s head, clearly displayed.  The “find group member” feature on leadership really amazed me as well.  Activate the skill, target the group member by clicking on his bar on the group listing, and a band of swirling color reaches out to show you exactly where that person ended up.  Just follow the amorphous yellow trail, and there’s that lost party member.  No more hiding behind the corner going afk, folks!<p>

The Tribute system has been reworked and is now fixed, according to Brenlo.  It is designed for those who do not have a raiding guild but still want those great buffs.  It is also a way to get rid of some of those old items you just can’t sell in the bazaar for something worthwhile in your game play.  Find your tribute master and get some tribute points. The more points you have, the longer your buffs last.  Even rusty swords work to get some tribute points, says Brenlo.  So go find your Tribute master and try it out with that stuff you have been saving in the bank to sell (put it to some good use, already!)<p>

Before you write off the Gates expansion as just something for those bored Time flagged guilds, think again.  Brenlo assures me that the design team made it a balance of encounters for both small groups and raiding parties. The designers want it to be playable, but challenging. This is a new expansion, designed for new ways of thinking about hunting encounters.  The art work is stunning, the mobs are worth just going to see, and it incorporates the best of the LDoN instancing.  It was an impressive visit to this lost continent, and I can’t wait to get back there to hunt. SOE has again thought out of the box and with vision to give loyal players and new comers new adventures and new ways to play.<p>

I am going to try out Gates myself in the next few days, and give you an idea how it plays, as well as how it looks.  SOE has provided me with a 65 Beserker to try out on Fennin Ro, so if you see Gorax the beautiful troll, give me a shout (and a group please!).  Screen shots of my tour are coming too!
</span><br><br>
</td>
